{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":777,"record_hash":"sha256:5b72d4850d88f19e162dd257847bbb2334ca6011ffb9b437fdbaed627d616732","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:04:52.675Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Index rebuild is mostly about not letting an acceleration structure become secret truth.\n\nThings to think about:\n\n**What can go stale**\nThe index is derived from turn details. If a bug, schema change, or new heuristic changes how we canonicalize branch/review/change keys, old index entries may point to incomplete or wrong candidate sets.\n\nExamples:\n\n```text\nbranch: feature/x       -> hash A\nbranch: refs/heads/feature/x -> hash B\nreview: 1284            -> hash C\nreview: github-pr:1284  -> hash D\n```\n\nSame underlying target, different index key. That’s the rot.\n\n**Can we delete old entries?**\nGitMeta set indexes are append/add friendly. Removing stale entries may be annoying, especially if key canonicalization changes and we don’t know every old key. So don’t rely on precise deletion for v1.\n\n**Best v1 answer**\nUse versioned index namespaces:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index-version = 1\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:<branch-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:<review-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:change:<change-id> = set<session-key/turn-key>\n```\n\nThen if canonicalization changes:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index-version = 2\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v2:branch:<branch-key> = ...\n```\n\nReaders only use the current version. Old keys can rot harmlessly until a prune/rebuild tool exists.\n\n**Do we need rebuild in v1?**\nNot necessarily. For first implementation:\n\n- capture writes v1 indexes\n- readers query v1 indexes\n- if we change index rules later, bump namespace to v2\n- optional rebuild command can come later\n\nThis is fine because the source of truth is turn detail, not the index.\n\n**What should index values contain**\nUse `session-key/turn-key`, not just `turn-key`. That makes stale filtering cheap: read the turn detail, verify it still exists and still contains the queried evidence.\n\n**Reader should verify**\nEven after index lookup, don’t trust the index. Treat it as candidate discovery:\n\n1. query index\n2. load turn detail\n3. verify the branch/review/change is actually present in the turn\n4. score\n\nThis protects against stale indexes and old heuristic bugs.\n\n**Canonicalization decisions**\nWe need boring rules:\n\n- branch key: probably full ref when available, otherwise normalized branch name\n- review key: include provider/type, e.g. `github-pr:1284` or `gitbutler-review:<id>`\n- change key: canonical change id string\n- hash branch/review keys for storage safety, but keep readable values in turn detail\n\n**My call**\nFor v1:\n\n- version namespace in key path: `agentlog-index:v1:*`\n- no deletion/rebuild command required\n- reader verifies candidates against turn detail\n- bump namespace on key/canonicalization changes\n- add rebuild later only when needed\n\nThat’s enough. Anything more is ceremony.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:04:52.675Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}